  "prompt": "Programming Languages: What was the first REPL?",
  "response": "The first Read-Eval-Print Loop (REPL) is generally considered to be the one developed for the LISP programming language by John McCarthy and his team at the MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory in the late 1950s to early 1960s. REPL is a powerful feature that allows for interactive programming and debugging by taking single expressions, evaluating them, and then printing the result.\n\nLISP's REPL was instrumental in the development of many concepts in computer science and artificial intelligence, including symbolic computation and the development of function programming paradigms. The interactive nature of the REPL greatly facilitated experimentation and rapid development, which influenced the adoption of similar features in many subsequent programming languages.",
